docs.lead_paragraph: The rise of e-sports is no surprise to anyone who has followed the video game industry. They are expected to bring in more than $1 billion in global revenue this year, as millions of fans watch hundreds of events from all over.

docs.abstract: Two cultural projects that examine the Alabama city’s role in the civil rights movement are drawing throngs of visitors and encouraging a surge of downtown construction.
docs.snippet: Two cultural projects that examine the Alabama city’s role in the civil rights movement are drawing throngs of visitors and encouraging a surge of downtown construction.
docs.lead_paragraph: MONTGOMERY, Ala. — No other Southern city is arguably tied as closely to the history of race relations in America as Alabama’s capital, considered to be the birthplace of the civil rights movement. Not until recently, though, have the story of suffering and the response from activists translated into economic benefit for the 200-year-old river city.

headline.main: Revitalizing Montgomery as It Embraces Its Past
headline.print_headline: A City Confronts Its Racist Past, and Prospers

docs.abstract: The trade war intensified Monday, as Beijing allowed its currency to weaken and the Treasury Department labeled China a currency manipulator.
docs.snippet: The trade war intensified Monday, as Beijing allowed its currency to weaken and the Treasury Department labeled China a currency manipulator.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The trade war between the United States and China entered a more dangerous phase on Monday, as Beijing allowed its currency to weaken, Chinese enterprises stopped making new purchases of American farm goods and President Trump’s Treasury Department formally labeled China a currency manipulator.

headline.main: China’s Currency Moves Escalate Trade War, Rattling Markets
headline.print_headline: China Deploys Currency As Lever in Trade Feud, Jolting Global Markets

docs.abstract: The agreement, which received preliminary approval Monday, would end an array of lawsuits and investigations stemming from the exposure of the sensitive information of more than 147 million people.
docs.snippet: The agreement, which received preliminary approval Monday, would end an array of lawsuits and investigations stemming from the exposure of the sensitive information of more than 147 million people.
docs.lead_paragraph: The credit bureau Equifax will pay about $650 million — and perhaps much more — to resolve most claims stemming from a 2017 data breach that exposed sensitive information on more than 147 million consumers and demonstrated how little control Americans have over their personal data.

headline.main: Equifax to Pay at Least $650 Million in Largest-Ever Data Breach Settlement
headline.print_headline: Record Data Breach Settlement Will Cost Equifax $650 Million

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Justice Department is moving closer to approving T-Mobile’s $26 billion merger with Sprint, but only if the companies sell multiple assets to create a new wireless competitor, according to three people familiar with the plan.

headline.main: Sprint and T-Mobile Merger Approval, Said to Be Near, Could Undercut Challenge by States

docs.abstract: Mr. Epstein, charged with sex trafficking, cultivated an intimate, yearslong relationship with Leslie Wexner — and proceeded to get extraordinarily rich.
docs.snippet: Mr. Epstein, charged with sex trafficking, cultivated an intimate, yearslong relationship with Leslie Wexner — and proceeded to get extraordinarily rich.
docs.lead_paragraph: In May 1997, Alicia Arden, a model in California, was introduced to a man who identified himself as a talent scout for Victoria’s Secret. He invited her to his Santa Monica hotel room to audition for the brand’s catalog. When she arrived, Ms. Arden said, the man grabbed her, tried to undress her and said he wanted to “manhandle” her. Ms. Arden, then 27, fled in tears.

headline.main: How Jeffrey Epstein Used the Billionaire Behind Victoria’s Secret for Wealth and Women
headline.print_headline: Epstein Soared on a Friendship With Few Limits

docs.lead_paragraph: Wells Fargo has begun an “extensive review” of the way it closes customers’ accounts and the fees it charges some customers even after their accounts are supposedly closed, its chief executive, C. Allen Parker, said in a letter to Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts.
